OpenSCAD parametric script to generate a 3D printable tie. This differs from most others in that it allows you to easily make diagonal stripes in the tie by angling the tie, slicing it into sections and swapping filament colours. It also is assembled using strapping/webbing and a more complex neck piece which should allow it to be worn in a more standard/traditional way! I have seen several tie designs on thingiverse recently and I've wanted to make one myself. Specifically I have been mystified as to why I've not seen a wide strapping type material used to hold the pieces together and wrap around the neck comfortably. Equally I am amazed that no-one (as far as I have seen) has made a diagonally striped tie using filament swapping. This design is inspired by the other ties recently on thingiverse but is all original work. @version attempt 3
@date 2012-06-09 ISO Standard YYYY_MM_DD format @todo
make parametrically positioned mouse ears @warning
This is a VERY long print (+5hrs on Thing-o-Matic)
filament changing or multi extruders will be required to get stripes!
I have not assembled one of these yet so am not sure how it will work out
In order to have the bottom part NOT fall off you will need to ensure that the little angled cutout at the end is fully in the bottommost part fo the tie (you may need to manually adjust its position to be so) @note
Changes from previous versions:

  • integrated cutout and other 2 components (neck thing and actual tie)

    • @attention

• Download Openscad script and set the values in the uservariables* section to reasonable values for a printable tie of your dreams
  • Generate .stl
  • Print all the sections (insert different coloured filaments where you want your stripes to be)
  • Clean out plastic in all the recesses and cutouts
  • Thread strapping/webbing through the internal cutouts in the tie and neck piece leaving enough space for your neck and some extra for tightening
  • After pulling one end of strapping through angled hole at bottom of tie and other end back through the bottom of the neck piece fold them over and either stitch or heat seal together so that can't go back through the holes
  • Wear a tie like-a-boss

title: Camera mount for Prusa i3 MK2S bed

description.text:
This allows a camera (I used a raspberry pi 2.1 one) to be attached to the bed of the Prusa i3 MK2S printer.

Update holder (v4 19/08/2017): Made the holder fit tighter, as after weeks of printing it became loose and I needed to insert something between holder and mount for a sufficiently tight fit

I used https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1568750 as camera frame, this fitted my camera best. When combining it with https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1646474 as arm attached to the printer, there were two problems: It was too close to the bed and tire wraps of the printer's smooth rods were in the way. I could not find another thing solving all needs, so I took it as an adventure to learn 3D printing and designing parts for it. It is my first attempt at this, quite new to the topic. I used Fusion 360 to design the three new parts.

The clips can be used on the camera mount and hold the flat cable in place. The camera frame slided into the simple part that I designed around it. I had to print that part with supports. Maybe someone can comment on how this can be done without, but with the needed opening for the cable, I found printing with supports most suitable.

The mount attaches without any gaps to the frame of my Prusa i3 MK2S. You need to use one 10mm M3 screw (takeit from you spare bag ;-) ) instead of the 8mm M3 screw provided. As the manual says: do not over tighten them, the thread in the bed is easily damaged. How it is desgned, it is for the right hand side of the bed. Mirror it in your slicer if you want it on the left side. As it was my first experience with CAD and Fusion 360, the first two STL have not the best XYZ direction. Rotate them a few times 45 or 90 degrees around well selected axes and you are fine. The clip is OK, (still learning).

Have fun in camera view on your 3D printed creations,

I used Octopi with Printoid, which is quite impressive on what it can do operating and monitoring your printer and your prints.

description.text:
This is a simple way to enlarge your print volume if you already have the AM8 built. This will increase your Y-Axis to 300mm and Z-Axis up to 300mm depending on your hotendand carriage design. There's only two parts to print and a few parts to buy. You will need to buy longer Y-Axis rods, longer Z-Axis extrusion, larger sub plate(H-Plate), larger bed heater and larger bed. Here is a list of the parts that I bought. You will need to print four bearing block spacers and one Y-Axis belt holder.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0045DWA9C/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://reprapchampion.com/collections/heated-beds/products/copy-of-3d-printer-mk2a-300x200-heated-bed-boro-glass-hardware-wiring-thermistor-kit

https://reprapchampion.com/collections/heated-beds/products/anodized-aluminum-y-carriage-plate-xl-300x200-prusa-i3-upgrade-reprap-3d-printer

2040x480mm extrusion 2 pieces
https://us.misumi-ec.com/vona2/detail/110302684350/?Inch=0

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00UR0N370/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00F2IQNX8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

What you need to do is remove the existing 440mm Z-Axis extrusions and put them in place of the existing Y-Axis 340mm extrusion. Then add the 2 new 480mm extrusions to the Z-Axis. Add the 2 new 495mm 8mm rods to the Y-Axis. Add the new subplate, heater and bed. I would not use the wire that comes with the bed it gets to hot, replace it with good quality silicon wire at least 14ga. Don't forget you will have to change you bed size in your slicer software and in Skynet/Marlin config file.

NOTE: To get the most amount of Z-Axis travel you will also have to do the 2020 X=Axis conversion and use two short bearing mounts. See photo of my printer above.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2439194

title: Llzbot Taz 6: Single Extruder Fan Grills and Housing and 3D screws

description.text:
A couple of my friends want a simple version of my fan grills for their single extruders.

{A note of caution:}

  1. The left fan grill and left 3D printed screws go to the left fan.

  2. The right fan grill and the right 3D printed screws go to the right fan.

  3. The front fan grill and the front 3D printed screws go to the front fan.

  4. After install the housing and the fan grills on the extruder, make sure both the right and left switches can be activate by the extruder freely.

  5. Move the extruder (SLOWLY) all the way to the right to hear the right switch click.

  6. Move the extruder (SLOWLY) all the way to the left to hear the left switch click.

  7. When install the housings make sure the 3DGAIN side of the housing always face you. That side of the housing is a reference for future alignment of other designs.

Enjoy!

title: Measure the coefficient of friction between materials

description.text:
Back to school? Surprise your physics teacher with this scientific instrument.
A simple two component 3D printed device allows you to measure the coefficient of friction between two materials, dry, wet or lubricated. The shaft is M3 and is fixed to the scale. The table rotates around it. The hole diameter fits to the M3 bolt in such a way that you have to screw the bolt into the table before fixing it with the nut to the scale. In this way there is enough friction to keep the table in position under any angle. Put a sheet of one material on the rotating table (fix it with double sided adhesive tape). Put a piece of the other (or the same) material on top of it and slowly increase the angle of the table. At the moment the object starts to move, read the value.
Repeat this two times and take the average value out of three. The table gives the coefficient of friction, which is the tangent of the angle. This table is printed on the instrument in steps of 0.1.
If you prefer a value in degrees, take the second version.
An overview of several material combinations is can be found on http://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/friction-coefficients-d_778.html
https://youtu.be/07UaIDhy9jU

title: Anet A6 Power Supply Cover and Switch Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a power supply cover and switch holder for Anet A6 (not valid for Anet A8 as far as I know). It is one of the safest upgrades for your printer in order to avoid electrical accidents. I also used a fused switch which also gives an extra of security.

As an example you can use a switch like this: https://www.amazon.com/URBEST-Module-Switch-Certification-Socket/dp/B00ME5YAPK, you have to check that it's valid for the hole (I think this is a standard, but confirm yourself). You will need two M3 and nuts for switch fixation and one M3 screw to anchor it to power supply (you can use the spare screws from printer)

About the fuse, you can use 2A fuse (calculated for 180 W at 220V, although you can even use a bigger one keeping in mind that the higher, the more unsafe).

I printed it with 0.2mm layer height and 20 % infill, however, I highly recommend use a higher infill (about 50%) to improve the stiffness, which is important when plugging the power cord. I used PLA. Supports are needed, but they are small.

Don't hesitate to comment in case you need help about electrical connections or you want to leave any feedback.

Hope you enjoy!

description.text:
I thought I would build a working jack stand. This thing requires one yellow motor (can be obtained cheaply from Amazon https://www.amazon.com/Dimart-100RPM-Robot-Intelligent-Shaft/dp/B00PFBEMQC/), a single AA battery, and this thing (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9805). Print out the following quantities:
4x cap.stl (open end up)
2x crank.stl (flat section facing down)
2x pitman rod.stl (laying down flat)
1x platform.stl
1x rod.stl (see printing comment below)
2x samson stand.stl (laying down flat)
1x walking beam (video shows printing upside down. print with fork on the bed)

I found it easiest to print in the following groups:

  1. walking beam (with support and maybe a raft)
  2. rod (with support and likely a raft) laid down flat so the extrusion goes the length of the rod, 0.1mm layer.
  3. everything else (without support)

The anchor holes are just slightly undersized for M4 bolts so that you can tap them or drill them (I've tried both). For t-slot you just buy your preferred bolt and t-nut sizes and drill out the holes to fit with a hand drill (takes ~5 seconds each). The countersunk holes sink even allen bolt heads below the lenses (see pictures).

To complete the optical rail system you can use:
T-slot M4 thread nuts like these
M4 nuts like these or these from a kit with different lengths
These are appropriate 50mm lenses

Dec 2017 All updated to a version I have saved as "V22".
Step and Iges files available at Grabcad (https://grabcad.com/library/dag-geared-belt-extruder-1)
BOM:
3mm Pneumatic fitting, M5 (for outlet)
3mm id 7mm od 3mm thick ball races (four needed, fitted inside the 13 T gear/belt pulley)
(this is almost certainly overkill, and 2 would do, but they are cheap and fitting 4 is easier than trying to hold two in the correct places)
608zz ballraces (8mm id, 22mm od, 7mm thick) "skateboard ballrace", three required.
8mm *60mm bolt and nuts for main drive (you may also need washers to help this fit "nicely")
M3 bolts : 8mm (three for holding the motor)
20mm two for the casette
30mm, three needed, two for the outlet, one to hold the casette in the main bodies.
35 to 40mm for the tensioning screw (you may be able to use a 30mm)
M3 brass press in inserts (4mm dia) five needed
M3 grub screws or short 8mm bolts and nuts for the Herringbone gear version.
One M3 nut for the tensioning screw (or use a brass insert)
M5 30mm bolt and nut for 20T idler pulley

GT2 parts:
200mm belt
20Tooth 8mm Drive Pulley with grub screws to hold to 8mm shaft (for main drive )
20Tooth 5mm hole 9 mm thick Idler Pulley (I used a version with bearings)
(or use a standard 20Tooth 5mm hole "Drive Pulley" and the alternate Motor bodyside STL)

If using the Belt drive and not the herringbone drives you will need:
20T GT2 5mm hole Drive Pulley
60T GT2 8mm hole Drive Pulley (or print one of you are adventurous)
200mm GT2 belt (same as the main traction belt)

This was designed to be used with delta printers, with the outlet fitted to 20x20 framework at the top of the printer. The outlet can be fitted to the printer first, and then the main extruder "slots" onto the outlet, and is held by two M3 bolts. This makes it easy to remove for adjustment/servicing.

Other Notes:

Oct 2017 Slightly revised outlets and drive gears.
The 41 tooth gear now has a very slightly smaller "belt" drive diameter compared to the originally published version. This reduces "slip" between the 13:41 gear ratio and the belt movement on the two parts.
The outlet path has also been revised to better match the actual filament path as it exits the drive. This results in a filament path 5 degree off from the "as designed" path, and allows less lateral movement of the filament in the extruder, preventing the filament from bending under more extreme loads.

4 Aug 2017 NOW updated with Large Herringbone gears..Made using
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10707 (thanks!)
Video of updated version added. Initial tests show it is capable of pushing filament at about 2.5 to 3kgf before the torque of the motor is overcome.
Note it is "upside down" in the STL full model....The filament comes OUT of the connector shown on the top in the model. The "Belt" and "Filament" in the drawings are only approximate, but show their general positions.

https://youtu.be/Kta063mSm8k

Experimental belt extruder
Design started as a version of the gunstruder. with elements of Vaeder.
The main v drive is geared to one of the 20T GT2 pulleys. This dramatically improves the drive. (like the librostruder and vaeder).
I have used pulleys that can be purchased easily on ebay or similar.

I have tested this with my force filament sensor (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2429390) and in the video cut I pan to the screen displaying the force applied. This is about the same or more force than I can get from a Wade extruder before it strips the filament. The advantage of the GBE extruder is that it does not damage the filament. Once the filament pressure reduces (by extruding ) the filament is again driven at full force. This is in sharp contrast to a wade or similar, where once the filament strips, it can only drive at about 0.5kgf if that.

I think it could be improved by changing from the belt gearing to the herringbone gearing as used in some wades, this should increase the torque on the filament further for a given motor.

Notes:

You should not need supports, but parts will need to be rotated to place their flat surfaces "down".
The tension parts are at some funny angles so need care to place "flat".
I printed with a 0.4mm nozzle, 0.2mm layers.
I have versions in both ABS and PLA.

Open all holes to 3mm or 5mm as required. In all cases you can use longer screws, and this may assist assembly.
Once you have assembled the cassette of the main printed gears, it is a good idea to run them in and make sure they are free to move. Some filing of the gears may be necessary at this point....The bearings should be fitted in the pulleys so that the pulleys do not scrape on the insides of the cassette body.

Bearings are 608 roller skate types. and 3mm7mm3mm small bearings for the printed GT2/gear pulley. You can use two bearings in this pulley plus a spacer, but it can also take 4 bearings, which can be easier if the spacer is hard to make.
Images below show the belt driven version, but the Herringbone gear version is exactly the same, .... just with Herringbone gears!.

This was the original with belt gears,Note that the bolts in the min body have now been rotated by 180. This makes them easier to remove once the herringbone gear is in place.The herringbone gear version increases the force available to the extruder. New version uses two 20mm M3 bolts Note: New version has the bolts reversed for easier access with the herringbone gear.

Steps:

1) Bend the legs of the LEDs accordingly.
2) Glue the LEDs to the allocated locations.
3) Solder a wire to each pin of the on/off switch.
4) Insert the on/off switch into the switch box.
5) Complete the circuit on the battery holder (you can a ball of solder into each of the provided circle and link them up with a wire, or anyway you like)
6) Solder up the rest of the circuit accordingly in "parallel", NOT SERIES.
7) Test the circuit. If it works, proceed to step 8, if it doesnt work, check for errors and fix them.
8) Glue the battery holder and the switch box to the back of the base.
9) Assemble the rest of the parts and glue them in place.
10) Turn the LEDs on, take some photos. Find a mirror, strike some poses, take some selfies. Enjoy!

description.text:
This is an attempt to create a parametric version of the famous SCxUU type linear bearing housing/holders. This design is a bearing "snap in" design, you simply click your bearings in the housing as the inner rims will hold the bearings in place. The fastener holes are small enough to insert an M4 tap to make the threads, screwing them in without a tap will also work. Feel free to experiment!

The rendered STL here can hold the RJMP-01-08 linear bearings with a diameter of 16 mm (note the RJ4JP-01-08 bearings are 15 mm in diameter, you can simply alter the design parameters in Fusion360 to create your own STL files).

I replaced the metal blocks with this design on the extruder carriage which now runs way more quite. Next step is replacing the heatbed carriage bearings. Note that is might be wise to increase the width between the screw holes a little bit, as it was a little bit tight.

Bearing housings and Igus style bearings are now also installed on the y carriage; the noise during printing is now reduced to such a level that I can print in the living room without upsetting the wife when she's watching TV! :)

title: Mounting/Isolating Parts for G10/CF/GF/Alloy DJI Arms (Flamewheel, Discovery)

description.text:
• Consider untested and experimental!!

Having read about vibration issues using aluminium arms, needless to say I was intrigued.
After installing the arms it became clear the frame now acted like a large tuning fork!

Even with well balanced everything, at certain RPM's propeller tips would flutter, and at other RPM's centre of frame would judder (heard with onboard mic).
Before changing to different size arms, motors and propellers in an attempt to change the natural resonant frequencies, I came up with these parts.

Motors, arms and frame are (somewhat) isolated from each other with 3d printed flexible filament (TPE) washers and bushings.
Arms took 2.5mm bolts through 3mm holes in the frame, so this gap is filled using the TPE M2.5_to_M3_soft_adapter+washer.stl thing.
While just the frame/arms isolation appears to have done the trick, I jumped on the hype train and soft mount the motors too. Has potential to make things better, worse or have no effect besides more "juicy" flying (whatever that means lol).

Without the spacers and soft mounts, tapping the end of an arm resulted in a sustained "gonggg"! After the modifications it's now a quick "thud". Not very scientific I know..

  • Important Note: Test thoroughly in a safe manner.
    While the idea is to separate the components and lower frequency coupling effects, these modifications also have the potential to INCREASE the amplitude of certain standing waves capable of ruining more than your video!

Every setup is different, this is not a solution but rather another option to experiment with.

Tourque down the TPE spacers until they grip the frame firmly, too tight and they'll have little-to-no effect.
Threadlock all round!

For each arm you will need to print:
x6 TPE M2.5_to_M3_soft_adapter+washer.stl (use slicer's "one at a time feature")
x6 TPE 8mmx0.8mm_washer_m2.5.stl
x1 (or x2) TPE 16x9x1.stl (1mm remix of Lefty9's soft mounts)

Hardware per arm:
x8 Metal M2.5 inside diameter washers ~7-8mm outer
x4 Metal M3 inside diameter washers (for motor mounts)

Careful not to damage motor windings with long screws if coming from thick plastic dji arms.

7mm spacer block thing with cutout for esc wires is to retain 37mm dji arm height with 30mm tall alloy arms, to be printed in nylon/abs/pet. Uses x2 bolts (12mm of exposed M2.5 thread).

0.2 Layers, 0.3mm Nozzle

100%

description.text:
Designed by Wang Mechanical

Updates

Please click the "Watch" button to get notified about any new update.

20171211 Update

  • A new base assembly of CRUSH is tested and uploaded, to create a highly stable universal version. This rail track design can support filament spools with various width from 25 mm to 95 mm.

20171128 Update

  • A sturdy securing clamp design is tested and uploaded, to further reduce the chance of a tip-over due to human errors.
  • A 125.5 mm variant of CRUSH part A and B (suggested by user @bdietrich7) is uploaded, as well as a longer base model.

20170803 Update

  • The original CRUSH (V1) was tested with 1 kg Makergeeks filament spool but some users reported incompatibility with other brands. Therefore a new design (V2) is presented to possibly accommodate all popular 1 kg spools (eSun/Inland, Hatchbox, Makergeeks, Silver, Taulman tested).

Introduction

CRUSH (CR-10 Ultimate Spool Holder) is a complete redesign of TUSH (The Ultimate Spool Holder) to fit on the control box of a Creality CR-10 printer. With base parts printed, CRUSH can be universally used on any 3D printer.

Design

The original TUSH is a wonderful design with a major drawback: when the filament is pulled rapidly in an angled direction, TUSH and the spool on it are likely to tip over. Instability exists on some other remixes that attempt to adapt TUSH for CR-10. CRUSH crushed (sorry, had to do it) this tip-over problem with higher barricades and a better locking mechanism, but without adding more material. The Warren-truss design of the barricade adds not only stability but also some engineering aesthetics.

Installation

CRUSH is easy to print and install. Please measure the horizontal span of your CR-10 control box before choosing to print the 124.5 mm, 125.5 mm, or 126 mm version, as control boxes from different vendors may not share the same dimensions.

CRUSH CR-10 Version

Print the following items to use CRUSH on a CR-10 control box:

  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_XXX.Xmm_A
  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_XXX.Xmm_B
  • 4 x WM_CRUSH_V2_Clamp (optional but highly recommended)

CRUSH Universal Version

Print the following items to use CRUSH on any flat surface:

  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_XXX.Xmm_A
  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_XXX.Xmm_B
  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_Base_A
  • 2 x WM_CRUSH_V2_Base_B

Once you finish printing all necessary items, just snap everything together following the preview images. Enjoy!

Reference

I have been using a real J-Head now for 4 years and some change and I finally decided the old hotend needed to be changed. It snaps on as tightly as the original V6 clone fan did and even with the inevitable backflow the 40mm just puts out way more air than the 30mm does.

I recently made my own FPV drone and decided I needed to have a landing platform for it. The landings platform will be controlled by an Arduino Nano and by 8 AA batteries (might be more if the LED's need more power).

Perks

  • Easy to scale/size the model due to the use of equations.

The models also includes a bill of materials that shows all the products you need. I have also included a link to the product using my Banggood referral code.

Scaling
Scaling can be done in two ways. You can scale the model in Adobe illustrator. Another way of scaling the model is to edit the equations text file. When you decide to change the model you will need to make a new drawing a good tutorial for that is found here. www.youtube.com/watch?v=hZrGLonrpt8&t=191s

A handy tip for converting the drawings to Adobe Illustrator is to change the border colors to red. In SOLIDWORKS go to System options/colors/visible model edges.

When there is something wrong with the model please let me know so I can fix it as soon as possible.

Notes
Interested in buying one please contact me via the GrabCAD or Thingiverse messenger. I could also include a custom engraving into the model. The price depends on the size and shipping costs. Don't worry I won't charge much since I love to build stuff.

title: 5 to 40 degree GoPro Session Mount for a Martian 5"

description.text:
Recently I have been building a quadcopter for my brother. This will be his first Kwad so I decided to build it on a budget... The frame I chose to use was the Martian-255, the Martian is a Chinese clone of an impulseRC Alien 5" Clone https://impulserc.com/collections/alien.

However, the Martian at £26 is a good budget frame being; light, compatible with all common parts, and it flies well too.

Martian Frame can be bought from RadioC
http://www.radioc.co.uk/Martian-255-Alien-Clone-Carbon-Fiber-Drone-Frame-p/19902.htm

These GoPro session mounts are for a Martain 5" quadcopter designed to cover angles between 5 to 40 degree in 5-degree steps. The is the 2 iteration of the design and now has wider uprights on the front face, and the design has been optimised to print well with TPU.

This design was inspired by @drewcamden aka LeDrib... http://shop.miniquadclub.com/shop/accessories/mqc-fusion-session-cage-mount-by-le-drib/

Drew's session mount was designed for the MiniQuadClub Fusion Frame - http://shop.miniquadclub.com/shop/frames/mqc-fusion/

But this range of mounts has been designed specifically for the Martian 5", and is part of series of mounts which range from 5 to 40 degrees, in 5-degree steps. Whilst a strap is not needed with this design, I would suggest one is used if you expect to be flying & crashing hard.
